Test for Anova Function

stat_check <- function(results_alpha, diversity_metric, group_variable){
args <- substitute(diversity_metric ~ group_variable, list(diversity_metric = as.name(diversity_metric), group_variable = as.name(group_variable)))
div_model <- lm(args, data = results_alpha)
print("shapiro_test")
print(shapiro_test(residuals(div_model)))
print("levene_test")
print(levene_test(args, data = div_model))

print(ggqqplot(residuals(div_model)))
}

# fixing factored BMI
new_sam$BMI_title <- "overweight"

chi-square fun times

Chi-square test examines whether rows and columns of a contingency table are statistically significantly associated.

Null hypothesis (H0): the row and the column variables of the contingency table are independent. Alternative hypothesis (H1): row and column variables are dependent

new_sam$BMI_group <- factor(new_sam$BMI_group, levels = c("healthy_weight", "overweight", "obesity"))


chitest2 <- new_sam %>% 
  group_by(k_8, BMI_title) %>% 
  dplyr::count(BMI_title) %>% 
  dplyr::mutate(cluster_n = case_when(
    k_8 == 1 ~ 85,
    k_8 == 2 ~ 89,
    k_8 == 3 ~ 65,
    k_8 == 4 ~ 61,
    k_8 == 5 ~ 59,
    k_8 == 6 ~ 58,
    k_8 == 7 ~ 37,
    k_8 == 8 ~ 19,
  ))

chitest2$n_norm <- chitest2$n/chitest2$cluster_n

bplot <- chitest2
  
  
balloonplot(bplot$k_8, bplot$BMI_title, bplot$n_norm, xlab = "", ylab = "BMI", main = "Clusters", label = FALSE, show.margins = FALSE)

chitest2 <- chitest2 %>% 
  select(-n_norm, -cluster_n) %>% 
  pivot_wider(names_from = k_8, values_from = n) %>% 
  data.frame()

row.names(chitest2) <- chitest2$BMI_title

chitest2 <- chitest2 %>% 
  select(-BMI_title) %>% 
  as.matrix() 



chisq <- chisq.test(chitest2)

Alpha Div

results_alpha$k_8 <- as.character(results_alpha$k_8)

Testing Alpha div Anova

Observed

stat_check(results_alpha, diversity_metric = "Observed", group_variable ="k_8")
## [1] "shapiro_test"
## # A tibble: 1 × 3
##   variable             statistic  p.value
##   <chr>                    <dbl>    <dbl>
## 1 residuals(div_model)     0.868 1.34e-19
## [1] "levene_test"
## Warning in leveneTest.default(y = y, group = group, ...): group coerced to
## factor.
## # A tibble: 1 × 4
##     df1   df2 statistic     p
##   <int> <int>     <dbl> <dbl>
## 1     7   465      1.26 0.267

The result of the Shapiro test is that the observed data is NOT normal (since the p-val is significant). This means we’ll need to use the non-parametic test, kruskal-wallis.

The result of the levene test is that the p-val is insignificant, therefore the variances across groups are not different.

As the data is non-normal yet homogeneous, we will need to do the wilcox_test for posthoc analysis.

Whoa all the alpha diversity metrics are significantly different for each cluster… somewhat surprising? I mean, each cluster is based off of urobiome profile… but I don’t think that necessarily accounts for alpha diversity. It looks like Observed is pretty similar, so let’s take a closer look at that.
